<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <teiHeader>
        <fileDesc>
            <titleStmt>
                <title>Apparatus List for Lectio 34</title>
            </titleStmt>
            <publicationStmt>
                <p></p>
            </publicationStmt>
            <sourceDesc>
                <p></p>
            </sourceDesc>
        </fileDesc>
    </teiHeader>
    <text>
        <body>
            <div>
                <listApp corresp="#l34-pqoapi">
                    <app to="#l34-Aostest">
                        <lem/>
                        <rdg wit="#R #SV" type="intextu">in</rdg>
                        <note xml:lang="en">We chose to omit "in" in the edited text despite its presence in witness R and SV because we think the sentence makes the most sense where "theologia" functions as the subject of the verb "dirigit." This is also supported by witness V which varies too wildly to include in the apparatus, but whose meaning suggest the reading chosen here</note>
                    </app>
                    <app to="#l34-A1">
                        <lem/>
                        <rdg wit="#R" type="add.sed.del.">
                            <del>de</del>
                        </rdg>
                    </app>
                    <app to="#l34-oposic">
                        <lem>sic</lem>
                        <rdg wit="#S" type="om."/>
                        <note xml:lang="en">We choose to include sic here for two reasons. First where meaning is not at issue we attempt to follow witnesses R and SV. Second, the addition of "sic" does not alter the meaning in any significant way, but helps to suggest that a clause of indirect statement is to follow and that primum esse is not the direct object of "declarare" but actually the subject of the indirect statement that follows.</note>
                    </app>
                </listApp>
                <listApp corresp="#l34-eeqcphf">
                    <app to="#l34-Asitcer">
                        <lem>certa</lem>
                        <rdg wit="R" type="om."/>
                        <note xml:lang="en">That "certa" should be included seems demanded by the sense of the text which questioning whether or not human investigation is certain, and suggesting that it will never be "certa" without theology and wisdom.</note>
                    </app>
                    <app to="#l34-Ahocind">
                        <lem>indiget</lem>
                        <rdg wit="R" type="om."/>
                        <note xml:lang="en">Including "indiget" is supported by both S and SV and by the fact that the sense of the text rendered obscure without it</note>
                    </app>
                    <app to="#l34-Asaptra">
                        <lem>tradidit</lem>
                        <rdg wit="S">tradit</rdg>
                        <note xml:lang="en">We prefer both to follow R and SV where we can and the past tense to refer to Lombard's historical (past) treatment of the issue.</note>
                    </app>
                    <app to="#l34-ponhui">
                        <lem>huiusmodi</lem>
                        <rdg wit="#R">huius</rdg>
                        <note xml:lang="en">While a minor, the stronger reading seems to lie with S and SV since "huiusmodi" make it clear that the author is referring to the particular definition of happiness discussed by Lombard.</note>
                    </app>
                </listApp>
                <listApp corresp="#l34-spetse">
                    <app to="#l34-Aessigi">
                        <lem>igitur</lem>
                        <rdg wit="S" type="om."/>
                        <note xml:lang="en">The addition of "igitur" is chosen because it is an important indicator that the final clause should be read as a consequence following from the preceding premisses.</note>
                    </app>
                </listApp>
                <listApp corresp="#l34-isnfsa">
                    <app to="#l34-Afinsed">
                        <lem/>
                        <rdg wit="#R" type="sed.add.del.">
                            <del rend="strikethrough">na</del>
                        </rdg>
                    </app>
                    <app>
                        <lem>finis</lem>
                        <rdg wit="#R #SV" corresp="om."/>
                        <note xml:lang="en">While all things being equal we tend to privilege witnesses R and SV, we here choose the reading in S because of preference for the most explict reading. In other words, where a word is stated in one witness and reasonable left for the reader to supply in another witness, we will privilege the reading that states the word explicit to avoid ambiguity wherever possible.</note>
                    </app>
                </listApp>
                <listApp corresp="#l34-iichbf">
                    <app to="#l34-Aesster">
                        <lem/>
                        <rdg wit="#R" type="corr.">
                            <corr corresp="#l34-Chabnis"><del rend="expunctuated">habitudines</del><add>beatitudinis</add></corr>
                        </rdg>
                    </app>
                </listApp>
                <listApp corresp="#l34-iofpef">
                    <app to="#l34-Aomnred">
                        <lem>redeant</lem>
                        <rdg wit="#R #SV">redeunt</rdg>
                        <note xml:lang="en">We have chosen the subjunctive reading to keep this clause in step with the precedeing parallel clause ("quod sit principium" that uses the subjunctive "sit" in all three witnesses.</note>
                    </app>
                    <app to="l34-Adeoqui">
                        <lem>qui</lem>
                        <rdg wit="#R #SV">quod</rdg>
                        <note xml:lang="en">Here we choose "qui" over "quod" because it helps emphasize that it is God "who" is the fundamental principle</note>
                    </app>
                </listApp>
                <listApp corresp="#l34-eeiiep">
                <app to="#l34-Ascidil">
                    <lem>diliges</lem>
                    <rdg wit="#R #SV">dilige</rdg>
                    <note xml:lang="en">We choose "diliges" because this is more in keeping with the form of the quotation - -  in the biblical text.</note>
                </app>
                <app to="#l34-Aetmmax">
                    <lem/>
                    <rdg wit="#R #SV" type="intextu">et maximum</rdg>
                    <note xml:lang="en">We choose to omit "et maximum" here to avoid the otherwise awkward phrasing "this command is the greatest and the greatest in the law through..." Instead we prefer "this command is the greatest in the law through which..."  </note>
                </app>
                    <app to="l34-Asennon">
                        <lem/>
                        <rdg wit="#R #SV" type="intextu">est</rdg>
                        <note xml:lang="en">We exclude the "est" present in witness R and SV because it confuses the sense and obscures the fact that "propter commodum" should be taken as part of the clause introduced by "scilicet" and should not function as an independent sentence.</note>
                    </app>
                    <app to="#l34-Aesthic">
                        <lem>hic</lem>
                        <rdg wit="#S">hoc</rdg>
                        <note xml:lang="en">While the reading here is a difficult and the abbreviation in S could possible read as "hic", it nevertheless is the same abbreviation which is used for "hoc" only a view words before. We choose the reading "hic," explicitly written in R and SV, because we understand the text to be saying: "and therefore, in this case (hic), it is a matter of use...".</note>
                    </app>
                </listApp>
                <listApp corresp="#l34-ufcega">
                    <app to="#l34-Aaligen">
                        <lem>generaliter</lem>
                        <rdg wit="#SV" cause="senseMistake">generatur</rdg>
                        <note xml:lang="en">The sense rather clearly demands "generaliter," but SV writes equally clearly "generatur" therefore simply makes an obvious mistake.</note>
                    </app>
                    <app to="#l34-Acumdil">
                        <lem>dilectione</lem>
                        <rdg wit="#S">delectatione</rdg>
                        <note xml:lang="en">The difference here is negligible, so we follow R and SV as is our habit when all else is equal.</note>
                    </app>
                </listApp>
                <listApp corresp="#l34-smssra">
                    <app to="l34-Asinerel">
                        <lem/>
                        <rdg wit="#SV" type="add.sed.del.">
                            <corr corresp="#l34-Caddeum">
                                <del rend="underline">ad deum</del>
                            </corr>
                        </rdg> 
                    </app>
                </listApp>
                <listApp corresp="#l34-escuca">
                <app to="#l34-Ausuqua">
                    <lem>quandoque</lem>
                    <rdg wit="#S" type="om."/>
                    <note xml:lang='en'>We include "quandoque" here as it makes the reading more explicit, noting that "use" functions "similiter" when it is understood in its most common form.</note>
                </app>
                </listApp>
                <listApp corresp="#l34-apapas">
                    <app to="#l34-Aalisum">
                        <lem>sumendo</lem>
                        <rdg wit="#R"><sic>semendo</sic></rdg>
                    </app>
                </listApp>
                <listApp corresp="#l34-apauca">
                    <app to="#l34-Aquofru">
                        <lem>fruendum</lem>
                        <rdg wit="#R">sumendum</rdg>
                        <note xml:lang="en">Witness R, in this paragraph and the previous seems a bit confused. Further the fairly clear "fruendum" in both S and SV suggest that this is the best reading. Also see the corresponding paragraph in V for such further clarification of the this paragraph and the previous.</note>
                    </app>
                    <app to="l34-Amoddis">
                        <lem>distinguitur</lem>
                        <rdg wit="#R">dicitur</rdg>
                    </app>
                </listApp>
                <listApp corresp="#l34-pdmimt">
                    <app to="#l34-Aeteint">
                    <lem>introducentur</lem>
                    <rdg wit="#S">introducetur</rdg>
                    </app>
                </listApp>
                <listApp corresp="#l34-paphsf">
                    <app to="#l34-Aestfin">
                        <lem>finita</lem>
                        <rdg wit="#SV">infinita</rdg>
                        <note xml:lang="en">The argument demands "finita," therefore witness SV has simply made a mistake.</note>
                    </app>
                    <app to="l34-Abonfin">
                        <lem>anima humana est finita igitur potest quietari in aliquo bono finito</lem>
                        <rdg wit="#R">finita</rdg>
                        <note xml:lang="en">R appears to have made a clear omission here, possibily by confusing the "finito" and the end of the argument with the "finita" near the beginning</note>
                    </app>
                </listApp>
                <listApp corresp="#l34-cdereq">
                    <app to="#l34-Aetqqui">
                        <lem>quietative</lem>
                        <rdg wit="#S">quietare</rdg>
                        <note xml:lang="en">Choosing the right reading here is difficult, neither reading makes the sense perfectly clear. Thus, we choose revert to our default and follow R and SV.</note>
                    </app>
                </listApp>
                <listApp corresp="#l34-iictia">
                    <app to="#l34-Aquacom">
                        <lem>commotio</lem>
                        <rdg wit="#S">motio</rdg>
                        <note xml:lang="en">It is important to choose the "commotio" reading here because the argument depends on the fact that inclination toward God requires God's own cooperation</note>
                    </app>
                </listApp>
                <listApp corresp="#l34-icmdoc">
                    <app to="#l34-Anoneri">
                        <lem>erit</lem>
                        <rdg wit="#S">est</rdg>
                    </app>
                    <app to="l34-Aetssic">
                        <lem>sic</lem>
                        <rdg wit="#S" type="om."/>
                        <rdg wit="#R" type="add.sed.del.">
                            <corr corresp="#l34-Cdtdtdt">
                                <del rend="strikethrough">dt</del>
                            </corr>
                        </rdg>
                    </app>
                    <app to="l34-Asitsib">
                        <lem>sibi</lem>
                        <note xml:lang="en">While we try to refrain as much as possible from editorial interventions, this addition seem required by the sense (that, in this case, God will be loved on account of the good he brings to one's self). It is supported by witness V, which varies to substantially to be included in the apparatus, but often provides key insight into the text. In this case V includes "sibi."</note>
                    </app>
                </listApp>
                <listApp corresp="l34-cqodoc">
                    <app to="#l34-Acumsit">
                        <lem>cum sit</lem>
                        <rdg wit="#R" type="om."/>
                        <note xml:lang="en">Including "cum sit" is an important element that helps us see the cuasal premise of the argument.</note>
                    </app>
                    <app to="l34-Aomncon">
                        <lem>etc</lem>
                        <rdg wit="#R #SV" type="om."/>
                        <note xml:lang="en">While this admission is fairly innocuous, it does help us see that the desired conclusion is supposed to follow from the preceding clause.</note>
                    </app>
                </listApp>
                <listApp corresp="l34-spnpep">
                    <app to="l34-Anonvid">
                        <lem>videtur</lem>
                        <rdg wit="#SV">vide</rdg>
                    </app>
                    <app to="l34-Asupali">
                        <lem>alia</lem>
                        <rdg wit="#S">omnia</rdg>
                        <rdg wit="#SV" type="corr."><corr corresp="#l34-Comnali">
                            <del rend="underline">omnia</del>
                            <add place="inline">alia</add>
                        </corr>
                        </rdg>
                        <note xml:lang="en">While the difference between "alia" and "omnia" in this instance makes a marginal difference, we decide to follow R and SV not only because this is our default practice but also because the correction in SV shows some intentional preference on the part of someone for "alia" over "omnia." In other words at some point, someone was faced with the same choice that we now face, and they chose "alia," so we have decided to follow suit.</note>
                    </app>
                </listApp>
                <listApp corresp="#l34-ineaaf">
                    <app to="#l34-Alibvol">
                        <lem>libertate voluntatis</lem>
                        <rdg wit="#R">voluntate liberatis</rdg>
                    </app>
                    <app corresp="#l34-Adeipra">
                        <lem>praevia</lem>
                        <rdg wit="#R">prima</rdg>
                    </app>
                </listApp>
                <listApp>
                    <app to="l34-Aestobi">
                        <lem/>
                        <rdg wit="#R" type="add.sed.del.">
                            <corr corresp="#l34-Cetetet">
                                <del rend="expunctuated">et</del>
                            </corr>
                        </rdg>
                    </app>
                </listApp>
                <listApp corresp="#l34-iddfqd">
                    <app to="#l34-Adicses">
                        <lem>se</lem>
                        <rdg wit="#R #SV">si</rdg>
                        <note xml:lang="en">While it is hard to find the direct quote that Plaoul is referring to, it seems much better to read this as "David says he kept the law" rather than "if he has kept the law"</note>
                    </app>
                </listApp>
                <listApp corresp="l34-isddpm">
                    <app to="#l34-Abontun">
                        <lem>tunc</lem>
                        <rdg wit="#S">ergo</rdg>
                        <note xml:lang="en">There is a little at stake here in meaning, thus we revert to our default practice of following R and SV when all else is equal</note>
                    </app>
                    <app to="#l34-Aboness">
                        <lem>esset</lem>
                        <rdg wit="#S">est</rdg>
                        <note xml:lang="en">Here, as with the variant below, we choose the imperfect tense since the argument is based on the fact that the premise is supposed to lead to a counterfactual consequence.</note>
                    </app>
                    <app to="#l34-Amagdeb">
                        <lem>deberet</lem>
                        <rdg wit="#S">debet</rdg>
                    </app>
                </listApp>
                <listApp corresp="#l34-ibiesm">
                    <app to="#l34-Abeaill">
                        <lem>illa</lem>
                        <rdg wit="#SV" type="add.">
                            <corr corresp="#l34-Cilllla">
                                <g ref="#carrot"/><add place="aboveLine">illa</add>
                            </corr>
                        </rdg>
                    </app>
                </listApp>
                <listApp corresp="#l34-esspca">
                    <app to="#l34-Asicvel">
                        <lem>vel</lem>
                        <rdg wit="#R">nihil</rdg>
                        <note xml:lang="en">"vel" is the right reading here because the sense the argument is saying "if this is true, then either it is true finitely which means... or it is true infinitely which means..."</note>
                    </app>
                    <app to="#l34-Anonpos">
                        <lem>posset</lem>
                        <rdg wit="#S">potest</rdg>
                        <note xml:lang="en">The imperfect is preferred because this is, once again, a counterfactual example.</note>
                    </app>
                </listApp>
                <listApp corresp="l34-iascam">
                    <app to="#l34-Aitearg">
                        <lem/>
                        <rdg wit="#S" type="intextu">et</rdg>
                    </app>
                    <app to="#l34-Aessmag">
                        <lem/>
                        <rdg wit="#R" type="add.sed.del.">
                            <corr corresp="l34-Campamp">
                                <del rend="strikethrough">amp</del>
                            </corr>    
                        </rdg>
                    </app>
                </listApp>
                <listApp>
                    <app to="l34-Aquiomn">
                        <lem>esse</lem>
                        <rdg wit="#S">omne</rdg>
                        <note xml:lang="en">We privilege "esse" because, despite the fact that R and SV clearly read "omne" in this instance, in the following paragraph they clearly use "esse" in a similar context. The "esse" reading is also supported by V.</note>
                    </app>
                </listApp>
                <listApp corresp="#l34-iidiie">
                    <app to="#l34-l34-Agrapos">
                        <lem>posteriores</lem>
                        <rdg wit="#S">posterior</rdg>
                    </app>
                    <app to="#l34-Aincpri">
                        <lem>priores</lem>
                        <rdg wit="#S">priorem</rdg>
                    </app>
                    <app to="#l34-Agraess">
                        <lem>esse</lem>
                        <rdg wit="#S" type="om."/>
                    </app>
                    <app to="#l34-Asiccom">
                        <lem>esse</lem>
                        <rdg wit="#SV" type="corr.">
                            <corr corresp="l34-Ccomcau">
                                <g ref="#carrot"/><add place="aboveLine">communicetur</add>
                                <del rend="underline">causetur</del>
                            </corr>
                        </rdg>
                    </app>
                    <app to="#l34-Asupper">
                        <lem>supra perceptivum</lem>
                        <rdg wit="#S" type="om."/>
                    </app>
                </listApp>
                <listApp corresp="#l34-uarcnf">
                    <app to="#l34-Adeninf">
                        <lem>infinita</lem>
                        <rdg wit="#R">finita</rdg>
                        <note xml:lang="en">The sense of the argumnet demands "infinita"</note>
                    </app>
                    <app to="#l34-Aadvest">
                        <lem>est</lem>
                        <rdg wit="#S" type="om."/>
                        <note xml:lang="en">As is our custom, we prefer the more explicit reading</note>
                    </app>
                </listApp>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
</TEI>
